@node "Document_7" " build"

 build


After starting the programme and  having  briefly  pressed  the  left  mouse
button,  in  order  that  the  "welcome requester" disappears, you will find
yourself at first automatically in the build mode. The iluminated LED on the
build  key  will confirm this. You can know really start with the drawing of
your flow-sheet. If you really want it, you can also press a couple of times
on the build button. With the mouse pointer of course.

In the build mode - and only in this mode - the lower fitting-keys, which
are necessary for sketching your flow-sheet, are activated.

The sketch-procedure itself consists in building up your flow-sheet with the
white painted building parts in a puzzle-like method. The building parts are
obtained easily by pressing on one of the above mentioned  fitting-keys  and
finally  pressing  once again on one of the new appearing fitting-keys which
mostly have some new direction variations of  the  original  chosen  fitting
part.

After having chosen a fitting part, the only thing to  do  is  to  move  the
mouse  pointer  with  this chosen fiting part to the place where you want to
fix it and then to press the left mouse button. Thats  all,  try  it  -  its
childs play.

From a normal tube without any fitting part to a complete  flow  sheet  with
all  needed  equipment  - all can be build at your own ideas only with a few
clicks.

For corrections you only need to place the right fitting part over the error
or simply cross it through (to be explained later) to erase. You can move or
copy single or whole groups of fitting parts with the slide key  (this  will
also be explained later).

Perhaps you have already noted, the black background on the screen where you
fix your fitting parts, are not entirely boundyless. About one fifth of this
black background - the lower part - cannot be utilised, no  matter  how  you
try.  This  area is for the use of error reports, comments and for the entry
of data.

@endnode

@node "Document_8" " test"

 test

When you press this key, then the programme "takes  a  look"  at  your  just
builded  flow-sheet  on  the  screen.  If  you  have  "forgotten" to build a
flow-sheet on the screen and  you  have  pressed  the  test  key,  then  the
programme will ask

"Where is the flow-sheet"

to "remind" you to build your flow-sheet on the screen.

Your flow-sheet will be scrutinized in the test-mode to  see  if,  e.g.  the
pumps  are  not  evenly placed, the check-valve are not fitted correctly, if
the flow-sheet is logically correct or it's not to complicated etc.

These flow-sheet "test" can take a few moments so try not to be impatient
during the report

"OK, just a moment, I'm testing the flow-sheet !"

is still on screen.

If appears the report

"OK, if you want press `data'"

that means your flow-sheet, sorry, your plant is error free  and  ready  for
further progress (but not necessary) e.g. change into the data mode.

Should the OK report not  appear,  then  one  of  the  undermentioned  error
reports will appear. They have the following cause:

"This flow sheet is just tested"

The programme tests a builded flow-sheet on the screen only  one  time.  You
have tried to test a just tested flow-sheet a second time.


"This part isn't complete connected"

Same as with a real installation, you just simply can't start  up  with  the
operation of a heatexchanger without having connected it correctly or let a
tube without ends. This means  that  all  connections  must  either  be  put
together  with  tubes  or  other  connecting parts. At inlets and outlets of
tubes you must connect inlet- and outlet-arrows.


"I'm missing an outlet in this line"

If you have a length of pipe,  then  under  normal  circumstances  you  have
always  a definedflow through direction. This means that the tube has always
an inlet and an outlet, regardless if something is fitted between the  tube.
You cannot therefore have an inlet at both ends, an outlet is missing.


"I'm missing an inlet in this line"

Similar to the last error report, only this time an inlet is missing.


"Which flow direction do you want ?"

When two pumps are set in opposite directions, the only one can be correct.


"This check valve isn't correct installed"

The flow direction of the tube is another than that of the check valve.


"What kind of flow sheet is that ?"

In all probability, a "balls up" has occurred in the flow sheet which  can't
be  defined.  Look again very carefully at your flow sheet and try to find a
logical explanation in the problem.


"Please think about this point"

Imagine you have `t-piece' from which you pump from  all  three  connections
away. On what part should the medium flow in ?


"You cannot pump steam"

You naturally cannot connect a pump on the steam outlet of a boiler.


"Steam from boiler must go out"

Steam cannot flow into the boiler.


"Feed water must go into boiler"

When you install a feed water pump for the boiler, then, please ensure
that it is installed in the correct direction.


"You cannot pump out from top of tank"

From the top you only can fill the tank.


"You cannot pump into bottom of tank"


From the bottom of tank you only can take from.


"There is no flow in this circuit"

If on a tube there is whether any  inlet  and  outlet  nor  any  pump,  then
nothing  can flow. And then of course nothing can be calculated. E.g. if you
don't want in- and outlets, than please don't forget the pump.


"Please separate this two heatexchangers"

If you connect two  heatexchangers  directly  together,  then  you  have  no
possibility  to  declare  or  to  calculate the temperature between this two
heatexchangers. Install  at  least  one  piece  of  pipe  between  this  two
heatexchangers.


"Please separate this heatexchanger from the tank"

You must install one piece of pipe between the heatexchanger and the tank,
otherwise the temperature between cannot be declared or calculated.


"Please check the connections of these heatexchanger"

A medium which passes one time through  an  heatexchanger  should  not  pass
immediate  (e.g. without passing through another heatexchanger) back through
the same  heatexchanger.  The  temperature  of  this  medium  would  endless
increase or endless decrease.


"Please check the connections of this heating coil"

You must connect to this heating coil circuit another heatexchanger, for
adding or discharging energie.


"One pump isn't OK, please correct"

One of the marked pumps is not correctly installed in the flow direction.


"The outlet pressure is higher than the inlet pressure"

Of course, the inlet pressure must be higher then the outlet pressure.


"Please check this steamtrap"

Probable you have installed the steamtrap in an incorrect flow direction.

@endnode

@node "Document_9" " data"

 data


When the test made by the programme of your just builded flow-sheet results
without any error reports, then you can change into the data mode.

When you try to bypass the test of your flow-sheet pressing immediately  the
data  key,  then  the programme would prevented it showing you the following
report:

"Please test your flow-sheet before use"

You must test your flow-sheet before using it. But even then,  although  you
have  tested the flow-sheet and still errors have ocurred, you cannot change
into the data modus. The following report will be showed

"Your flow-sheet isn't OK, please correct it before use"

E.g. only when the report

"OK, when you want press `data'"

is presented on screen, you can change into the data modus.

In the data modus you have the possibility to feed your just on  the  screen
builded  flow-sheet  with datas like tube diameters, pressures, temperatures
etc., to correct or delete this datas and to mark with a  "?"  (by  entering
the  "n"  from  the  keyboard) which values you want to let calculate by the
programm.

The only thing you have to do for showing the data field of a  certain  part
of  your  flow-sheet is to move the mouse pointer to this corresponding part
on your flow-sheet and to "klick" with the left mouse button (of  course  it
is  also possible to move the mouse pointer with the cursorkeys and to press
"enter" when arriving the coresponding part of your flow-sheet).

Immediately in the lower part of the screen there will appear one of this
data fields - depending on which part you have "clicked".
For example if you have klicked the inlet (-arrow) of a tube, the data-
field looks like the following:


      Inlet ................ Nr >        Flowrate (mass) .... kg/h
      Substance ...............          Density ........... kg/m3
      Pressure ......... bar ue          kinem.Viscos ...... mm2/s
      Temperature ........... C          dynam.Viscos ....... mPas
      Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Spec.heat-cap ... kJ/kg/K

or, if you klick on a tube, the folowing data-field will appear:

      Pipe ................. Nr >        Flowrate (mass)  ... kg/h
      Substance ...............          Speed ............... m/s
      Diameter ............. mm          Length of pipe ........ m
      Temperature ........... C          Zeta-value ............ -
      Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Roughness ............ mm

And the data-field of a displacement pump looks like the following:

      Displ. Pump .......... Nr >
      Substance ...............
      Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h
      Pressure ......... bar ue

Once a data field is on the  screen,  you  can  move  the  ">"  either  (and
ceremonius)  with  the cursor keys "up and down" and "left and right" or you
klick with the mouse the corresponding dimension where you wish the  ">"  to
be.
For example you have the above mentioned display  field  of  a  displacement
pump  and  want  to  input a Flowrate (vol) of 20 m3/h - simply move the ">"
either with the cursor keys or by mouse klick  to  the  Flowrate  (vol)  and
enter

"20"

that's all ! After pressing the enter key, the ">"  moves  automatically  to
the  next  dimension. Now you can enter more values, close the data field or
change to another data field. To change to another data field the only thing
to  do is to klick with the mouse another part of your flow-sheet on screen.
Immediately the new data field (corresponding then to the  klicked  part  of
the  flow-sheet)  will  appear on the lower part of the screen. If the mouse
pointer is located in the "empty room" between the parts of your  flow-sheet
and  you  press the left mouse button, then only the present data field will
disappear.

For values which should be calculated by the programm you must enter a

"n"

(like "n"ot calculated). On the corresponding part of the data field where
you have entered a "n" will appear the

"?"

Fundamental is (and that's important !):

You can place where ever you want a "n", e.g. question mark, to  demand  the
programm to calculate this value. You can also enter where ever you want (of
course it must be correct)  and  above  all  what  data  you  want  in  your
flow-sheet. It's not necessary to enter all data. The programm looks for the
needed values in your flow-sheet while the calculation.

Depending on your entered data the programme recognizes which  is  the  best
way for the calculation of the requested data.

Nevertheless there are some limits in entering "?" to calculate values.  The
programme isn't able to calculate the following:

Length of Pipes
Zeta-values
Roughness
Spec. Heatcapacity
Item Nr.

The Item Nr. are only additionally for you. It could be helpfull to have all
items  numbered  when  reading  the  itemlist  (see  project  menu)  of your
flow-sheet.

Normally there exists for each building part of  your  flow-sheet  an  extra
data field. But also here we have some exceptions:

Elbow
Cross       (it's not really a cross)
Instruments (they are for action mode)

If you want to delete a value in the data field, the only thing to do is  to
move  the  ">"  to the corresponding value and to press the blank key or the
Del key. To correct a value it's only necessary to overwrite the wrong value
with the new correct value.

@endnode

@node "Document_10" " calc"

 calc


If you think you have entered all of the calculations necessary  values  and
you  have  entered  the  "?"  for the requested values or you have installed
enough instruments, then you can press the `calc' button.  This  causes  the
programme  to  look  for  the  requested  values and to calculate them or to
prepare the calculations for the action mode.

If the programme misses some data for one calculation, it will  ask.  It  is
not  necessary  to  answer  every  question. If there is something you don't
know, klick the left mouse button and the  question  disappears.  There  are
usually more than one way to calculate things in a flow-sheet.

So, keep your shirt  on  when  there  appears  (from  your  point  of  view)
unnecessary questions. Klick one time to obtain the next question.

But, when the programme asks you an  essential  question  (you  will  notice
this),  you  must  answer  it.  If  you  still  refuse one of this important
questions, the programme will stop the current calculation.

If there is after all a ready calculation, the corresponding value  will  be
showed  within  a  data  field.  In this data field your entered "?" is then
replaced by this calculated value. Easy isn't it ?

The following reports that could appear during the calc mode are:


"...let me see !"

The programme is looking for all the "?" you have entered - the values  that
will be calculated. You could do anything.


"...I'm still on working..."

The programme is still doing his work. There is also nothing to do.


"...just a moment.."

The programme is just trying to "find out"  a  value.  There  are  sometimes
values  which  couldn't  be  calculated  mathematically.  In  that  case the
programme "approaches" step by step to a value. And  that  needs  of  course
some time, i.e. your patience.

If there appears one of the following reports, you  should  press  the  left
mouse  button  or the enter key to "fall back" to the data mode. Herein then
you could enter a missing value (for example a missing temperature around an
heatexchanger). Or in case of bad luck you could change your flow-sheet (for
example when you have forgotten a heatexchanger), i.e. to  go  back  to  the
build mode.

The reports are:


"I'm missing a temperature at this heatexchanger"

Obviusly there is one  more  temperature  around  the  marked  heatexchanger
necessary for the further calculations.


"I'm missing a temperature around this tank"

Obviusly there is one more temperature around the marked tank necessary  for
the further calculations.


"What kind of heatexchanger is that ?"


Considering the temperatures and the  massflows  around  this  heatexchanger
there  is  something  wrong  from  the energy point of view. Check your data
carefully once more.


"I'm missing the heaexchanger in this line"

Of  course  you  need  an  heatexchanger  when  you  want  to  calculate   a
temperature.  The only exception is when there is team in the line, then the
temperature could be find out by the pressure.


"There aren't any data for calculations"

No requested data ("?") and no data for the calculations has been  found  by
the  programme.  Possibly  you have pressed by mistake on the calc button or
you have selected by mistake the  "clear  all  data"  menu  item  which  has
cleared all your data.


"There are 2 different data of *"

The programme has found two different (paradox) data of the same  type.  For
example  2  different  temperatures  in  the same tube without heatexchanger
inbetween.
With the * the programme tells you with what kind  of  data  you  have  this
error  and  with  the both red frame in the flow-sheet you can see where the
data are.


"Where is your unknown value ?"

You have entered in an excellent manner all the data you know, but you  have
forgotten  to enter for the value you would have calculated by the programme
a "?".


"I think we have ice here"

Either  you  have entered a water temperature below 0 or you have taken away
so much energy from the water, that it freezed at the  place  with  the  red
frame.


"Where is the second pressure value ?"

Two pressure values are needed (p1 and p2) to let something flow in a  tube.
You  must enter the second pressure value or, if it isn't possible, you must
go back to the build mode to change your flow-sheet.


"This valve is to small"

Through a certain tube you would have a certain  amount  of  flow.  But  the
cv-value  of  the  installed  valve  in this tube is to small for this flow.
Either you increase the cv-value of the valve or the difference of pressure,
or  you  decrease  the  amount  of flow. Maybe you can bring to a close this
problem also by increasing the diameter of the tube  if  named  or  changing
other values.


"The pressure drop without valve is already to high"

By the amount of flow that you let pass through the tube the  pressure  drop
is to high. Change pressure or amount of flow or change the tube itself (for
example by increasing the diameter) to solve this problem.


"Please correct your data"

The calculations are here interrupted. To  continue  first  press  the  left
mouse  button,  then  correct  the  wrong data in accordance to the previous
reports and then press the calc button again.


"For this application the inlet pressure is to low"

For the entered flowrate in the pipe the marked inlet pressure  is  to  low.
Try a higher inlet pressure.


"There is no calculation of *"

Even after more than one request about the needed  values  for  the  running
calculations, you have refused the corresponding answers. So, no one of this
values will be calculated.


"I can't calculate the *"

There are certain things the programme can't  calculate  although  you  have
orderly  entered  a "?". Things like zeta-values, length of pipes, roughness
etc. This kind of data you must enter if they are needed for calculations.


"Check temperature or massflow of these heatexchanger"

There  is  something  wrong  with  the  energy   balance   of   the   marked
heatexchanger. Check carefully once more again the entered data.


"There is no difference between pressure p1 and p2"

If both pressures you have entered are the same and there is no  pump,  then
nothing will flow. At least a minimal presure difference is necessary to let
something flow.


"I need at least one pressure data for calculation"

Indeed the programme only is able to calculate pressure differences. So,  to
calculate  a  certain pressure it is essential to have at least one pressure
data.


If all with "?" market data have been  calculated  and  in  your  flow-sheet
there  isn't  any  instrument  to  observe,  then  the following report will
appear:

"...all data calculated !"

That means all the calculations have been realized.

If there are some instruments to observe in your  flow-sheet  (see  action),
then  the programme also supposes you will start with the simulation of your
flow-sheet. And then, after having done all the preparation succesfully, the
report

"I'm ready for action !"

will appear.

@endnode

@node "Document_11" " action"

 action


If you really have created in the build mode a  flow-sheet  without  errors,
and  you have filled this flow-sheet in the data mode with all the necessary
data, and you have prepared  your  flow-sheet  in  the  calc  mode  for  the
simulation,  and  you have enough instruments to observe in your flow-sheet,
then you can make the great step into the action mode by clicking the action
button.
If there is something wrong and the  programme  will  not  change  into  the
action mode, one of the following reports will appear:


"Please press calc before action"

You have tried to move directly from the data mode to the action  mode.  You
must  press  the  calc button before. This is the only way the programme can
prepare the calculations for the action mode.


"There isn't any instrument to observe"

It's impossible to move to the action mode when there isn't  any  instrument
in your flow-sheet - without any instrument you cannot see anything.


"There is no action without the missing data"

During the calc mode the programme asked you for some  values.  This  values
you  havn't entered, so the programme couldn't calculate some necessary data
for the simulation.
Without this data there is no action. Try calc again and enter  the  missing
data.

Only when the report

"I'm ready for action !"

appears on screen you can change into the action mode by clicking the action
button.  And  only  then you can sit back in your easy-chair looking at your
"running plant" on the screen. And if installed, to switch pumps on and  off
and to adjust valves.

But for Heaven's sake dont jump out of your easy-chair  when  a  temperature
doesn't  alter as quick as you expect or when the pump switch doesn't reacts
immediately. Have patience. There is an enormous amount of  calculations  to
do  to  simulate a "plant" the programme has never seen before. Besides, all
the searches and all the calculatins are done  one  after  another  and  the
programme must check if there is somebody who adjusts the valves or switches
the pumps on and off.


The adjustment of the valves

The adjustment (of the cv-value) of the valves is done by moving  the  mouse
pointer  to  the  corresponding  valve,  press  and hold down the left mouse
button, wait until the cv-value appears (needs possibly some time) and  then
by  moving  the mouse up or down, always holding down the left mouse button.
The cv-value in the display will change  in  accordance  with  the  vertical
movement  of  the  mouse.  While  holding  the  left  mouse button down, all
calculations  will  be  stopped.  After  release  the   mouse   button   the
calculations will continue.


The switchment of the pumps

To switch the pumps on and off move the mouse pointer over the pump you want
to  switch on or off and press the left mouse button. Possibly it needs some
time, but the display will then change either from "on"  to  "off"  or  from
"off" to "on" depending on its position it was before.


To jump out of the action mode

To jump out of the action mode there are 3 ways. You  can  click  the  build
button  (but  hold  the  mouse button down until the build button reacts) to
jump directly into this mode, or you can click the data  button  (hold  down
the  mouse button and wait until you see a reaction of the button) to change
data for example or you can select from the menu  additives  "stop  action".
You will then jump directly into the data mode.

@endnode


@node "Document_12" " help"

 help


All the green beginners who have started indiscriminately with their work in
this  programme  without reading the manual (RTFM) can find in this button a
short help.

@endnode
               

@node "Document_13" " fitting part keys "

 fitting part keys 

Tank

Pressing (i.e. mouse pointer over the fitting part key and pressing the left
mouse  button)  the  tank button there will appear 3 new tank buttons on the
screen. The 2 on the left side are tanks  with  a  heating  coil  (the  only
difference is the side for the connection of the heating coil) the right one
is a normal tank.


Boiler

Pressing the boiler button there will appear 5 new buttons on the screen.

The 2 on the left side are vaporizer/condenser each with  a  heating/cooling
coil on the left or the right side. If vaporizer or condenser depends on the
flow direction of the vertical line (flow up  is  vaporizer,  flow  down  is
condenser).  Button 3 and 4 (from left) are flash-steam-vessel, one with the
inlet on the left side and one on the right side. The last button (5)  is  a
normal boiler.


Pump

Pressing the pump button there will appear 2 new rows with each 4 pumps. The
upper  row  shows  centrifugal pumps, one for each flow direction, the lower
row shows displacement pumps, also one for each flow direction (right, down,
left  and  up). Each pump you have placed in your flow-sheet can be switched
"on" and "off" while running in the action mode.


Fan/Compressor

Pressing the fan/compressor button there will appear 2 new rows.  The  upper
row  shows  4  fans,  one  for  each  flow  direction, the lower row shows 4
compressors, also one for each flow direction (right, down,  left  and  up).
Each  fan  and  each  compressor  you  have placed in your flow-sheet can be
switched "on" and "off" while running in the action mode.


Heatexchanger

Pressing the heatexchanger button there will  appear  4  new  heatexchanger.
They differ from each other by the way they will be run through.


Steam trap

Pressing the steam trap button there will appear 4 new steam traps. One  for
each flow direction (right, down, left and up).
  

Hand-valve

Pressing the hand-valve button there will appear 2 new hand-valves. One  for
each flow direction (vertical and horizontal).


Check valve

Pressing the check valve button there will appear 4 new  check  valves.  One
for each flow direction (right, down, left and up).
  

Instruments

Pressing on the button with an instrument symbol there  will  appear  4  new
instruments.  They  differ  from  each other by the dimension they will show
during the action mode. From left to right a pressure gauge  (labelled  with
"PRESS"),  a thermometer (labeled with "TEMP"), a volume flow meter (labeled
with "VOL") and a mass flow meter (labeled with "MASS").


Control valve

Pressing the control valve button there will appear 2  new  control  valves.
One for each flow direction (vertical and horizontal). The speciality of the
control valves is the possibility to adjust the cv-value during the  running
action mode.


Inlet arrow

Pressing the inlet arrow button there will appear 4 new  inlet  arrows.  One
for each flow direction (right, down, left and up).
 

Outlet arrow

Pressing the outlet arrow button there will appear 4 new outlet arrows.  One
for each flow direction (right, down, left and up).
  

Straight tube

Pressing the straight tube button there will appear 3 new buttons. Two for a
simply  and  straight  piece of pipe (vertical and horizontal) and the third
button for two pieces of pipe lying one upon another (it is not a crossing).


Elbow/t-piece

Pressing the Elbow/t-piece button there will appear 2 new  rows.  The  upper
row shows 4 elbows, one for each flow direction of turn, the lower row shows
4 t-pieces, also one for each direction of branch  (right,  down,  left  and
up).


Remove fitting parts from the mouse pointer

If there is on of the above mentioned fitting parts on the mouse pointer and
you  want to remove it from the mouse pointer, please move the mouse pointer
over the right vertical button row and - thats  all,  the  fittimg  part  is
removed.

@endnode

@node "Document_14" " Further keys "

 Further keys


The X-key

Only just clicked, you will get a red "cross out" on your mouse pointer. Now
you  are  able to delete what ever you want in your flow-sheet. Move the red
cross out over the fitting part you will delete, press the left mouse button
and the part is deleted.

Also you are able to delete large parts of your  flow-sheet.  Move  the  red
cross  out while holding the left mouse button down. Similar to a cloth over
the black board in school all under the red cross out will be deleted.


The undo-key

If there is something you want to "undo", press one time the  undo  key  and
the last activity in the build mode will take back.


The move-key

If it is necessary to move or to duplicate parts of the  flow-sheet  or  the
entirely flow-sheet on the screen then you have with the move-key a helpfull
tool to do it. Press the move key one time and as reported on the bottom  of
the screen "frame and move block" you are in the move mode.

The part you want to move you must at first frame  and  cut  out.  For  this
please  move  the  mouse pointer to the top left side of the part, press and
hold down the left mouse button and drag to the right down of your part (you
will see a red frame), and then release the mouse button. You will then have
your part at the mouse pointer like any other fitting part from the key row.
You can fix your part on the screen by clicking the left mouse button.

If you want to remove your part from the  mouse  pointer,  please  move  the
mouse  pointer  over the right vertical button row and - thats all, the part
is removed.


The "move into the trashcan" key

Similar to the move-key, but with the difference  that  the  part  you  have
framed will deleted after have released the left mouse button.


The scroll bar

Like the screens of modern programmes it is  also  possible  to  scroll  the
screen  i.e.  your flow-sheet in DER_PROZESS_2.0. For this purpose there are
on the bottom and on the right side of the screen each one scroll bar.

If your flow-sheet is larger than the screen, you found for your orientation
(and  thats  new  !)  on the right down corner there a small "display" which
shows the actual position of your visible screen on your flow-sheet.

@endnode

@node "Document_15" " The DER_PROZESS-Menu"

 The DER_PROZESS-Menu


Of course and undoubtedly you  have  noticed  it,  also  DER_PROZESS_2.0  is
equiped with a menu. An accurate and nice detailed menu for each purpose.

But the DER_PROZESS_2.0 menu is not permanent active. Some menu  points  are
only  active  when  the selection of it is significant. The load and save of
flow-sheets for example is only possible when you are working in  the  build
mode and the substances menu is only after the selection of certain fittings
in the data mode active.


The menus in particular:

 @{" Project    " link "Document_16" 0}
 @{" Data       " link "Document_17" 0}
 @{" Units      " link "Document_18" 0}
 @{" Substances " link "Document_19" 0}
 @{" Additives  " link "Document_20" 0}
 @{" Preferences" link "Document_21" 0}
@endnode

@node "Document_16" " Project"

 The Project-Menu

Most on the left side and similar to the other programmes.


Load without data

However you have the possibility to load on the screen flow-sheets which you
have  builded  and  saved before with DER_PROZESS_2.0. After having selected
this menu there appears at first the standard file requester. Once you  have
loaded  a  flow-sheet  on screen you can follow with your further operations
i.e. building or testing it.


Load with data

Same as load without data but of course with data  (temperatures,  pressures
etc.).  You  can after load with data follow with the data input or directly
start with the calculations.


Insert

Herewith you have the possibility to insert parts of flow-sheets  which  you
have  saved before into the present flow-sheet on screen. The programme only
places new parts on the free positions inbetween the existing parts.


Save without data

If you have Flow-sheets which you found worth to save, here is the  suitable
menu point. After selecting you will found the file requester with which you
can do all the necessary operations to save the flow-sheet.


Save with data

As you can imagine, same as save without data but of course with  data  i.e.
with temperatures, pressures, etc.


Delete from disk

If there are some flow-sheets which do do not like any more, with this  menu
point  you  have the possibility to delete your flow-sheets from disk. Klick
twice, finished.


Save as picture

With this menu point you have the potentiality to save the actual flow-sheet
on the screen as an .ILBM file. This enables you to rework or print out your
flow-sheet with any other paint programme.


Clear screen

As the name says, with this menu point you clear the screen - and  also  all
the data.


Read itemlist

Herewith you can read  (multiview  will  be  started  automatically  by  the
programme)  an  internal  itemlist.  A  list  which  shows all parts of your
flow-sheet.


Save itemlist

And herewith you save the internal itemlist as an .ASCII file.


DER_PROZESS_2.0

Selecting this menu point you will be confronted  with  a  small  text  that
shows  name,  address  ect.  of  the programmer. It's the same you see after
starting the programme.


Workbench

If you will jump back to the workbench, you are also enabled to do  this  by
selecting  this  menu  point.  Of course normaly you do this by clicking the
screen swap symbol on the right upper corner.


Quit

If you are ready with DER_PROZESS_2.0 then you select this menu point to
quit the programme and to jump back to the workbench.

@endnode

@node "Document_17" " Daten"

 The Datamenu


Move data

With move data you have the possibility to move  data  in  your  flow-sheet.
I.e. to delete data at a certain point in your flow-sheet and to enter it to
another point in your flow-sheet. Of course, this will  only  be  done  when
both  points  you have selected are of the same type (for example you cannot
move pump data to a valve). You can select this menu point  either  with  or
without having selected yet a source point in your flow-sheet.


Copy data

Same as "Move data", but without deleting the data in the source point.


Clear point

After selecting this point you can clear all the data of  o  certain  point.
You  can select this menu point either with or without having selected yet a
point in your flow-sheet.


Clear *

If you need to clear for example all temperatures or all mass flow, you have
with this menu point the corresponding tool to do it.


Clear all data

And with this menu point you can clear all the hardly entered data  and  all
the calculated data.

@endnode

@node "Document_18" " Units"

 The unit menu


Everybody who have had something to do with the engineering of energetic  or
chemical plants, knows about the Punch and Judy show of the units. The worst
come to the worst if we have it to do world wide engineering.

But of course also here nothing disturbs  the  equanimity  of  the  user  of
DER_PROZESS_2.0. - there is a nice units menu !

You can where ever you want and when ever you  want  change  the  units,  no
matter  what  kind of units you like and no matter if you have an data field
just opened or not. Even in the action mode you can change  the  units.  But
don't forget, the instruments have only a limited display.


Normal

Select this menu point and you have the (in Germany) usual units.


SI

Select this menu point and all units are SI-units.


Old

Select this menu point and you have old (in Germany) units.


US

Select this menu point and you have the US-usual units.


Britisch

Select this menu point and you have (what a puzzle) the British-usual units.

The following menu points of the units menu are  to  select  for  what  ever
value you want the desired unit.

For example you have the possibility to work with  temperatures  in  degrees
Celsius,  Kelvin,  degrees  Fahrenheit  or Rankine, or to work with absolute
pressures or with gauge pressures. Test it.

@endnode

@node "Document_19" " Substances"

 The Substances menu


Certain medium like saturated steam or  water  are  very  common  fluids  in
energetic  and  chemistry plants. To avoid every time the ceremonious search
for the specific data (like density, viscosity, etc.) of one of this  normal
luids,  you can select in the substances menu the present fluid with all its
specific data.

The fluids are:

Steam (saturated steam)

Liquids
   Water
   Therm.Oil

Gases
   Air
   CO2  (carbondioxid)
   N2   (nitrogen)
   O2   (oxigen)
   He   (helium)
   H2   (hydrogen)

Before the selection of a certain fluid with the substances menu,  you  must
click in the data mode the point (pipe, inlet, outlet and pump) in which the
fluid flows.

After selection there must appear in the data field the name of the fluid.

The values for the thermal oil are average values, they do not  change  with
the temperature.


Delete

With this menu point you can delete the substance from one in the data  mode
clicked point. After selecting this menu point, the substance must disappear
from the data field.

@endnode

@node "Document_20" " Additives"

 The additives menu


Ready flow-sheet...

Often there is only a need of a simple heatexchanger or only a simple  piece
of  pipe.  To  avoid  each  time  the  circumstancial  building  of  such an
flow-sheet, you can select them from the menu. Naturaly this point  you  can
only select in the build modus. Not only the heatexchanger but also the pipe
are ready tested. If you want (not necessary)  you  can  change  immediately
into the data mode.


Heatexchanger

Builds a simple heatexchanger circuit on the screen.


Pipe

Builds a simple piece of pipe on the screen.


Help

The same function than the help button, helps all the  green  beginners  who
have  started  indiscriminately  with  their  work in this programme without
reading the manual (RTFM).
              

Stop action

Selecting this points stops the running action mode. If you could leave your
fingers  from the keyboard, the Esc-key has the same function than this menu
point.


Languages...

With this menu point you can switch between the both integrated languages
in the programme, English and German.

Read Manual

And selecting this menu point you will have the possibility to read (using
multiview) the manual.

@endnode

@node "Document_21" " Preferences"

 The  Preferences menu


Load Config

If you have put together your special unit configuration with which you like
to work and you have saved it before with the "save config" menu point, then
you can activate this configuration again by selecting this menu point.

If you select this point during the data mode with a data field on screen,
you will notice the unit change immediately.


Sichern Config

For saving your special unit configuration with which you like to work.

@endnode

@node "Document_22" " Hints and Tips "

 Hints and Tips


Nobody can read everybodys  thought.  I.e.  also  you  can  surely  build  a
flow-sheet in which the programme get confuse or has difficulties with it.

Therefore don't forget, even the best  chess  programmes  aren't  invincible
and,  DER_PROZESS_2.0  should  help  you  during engineering a plant like an
assistant and not like a strategy game. (or maybe  you  like  this  kind  of
strategy games ?)

But don't hesistate to build your flow-sheets  at  your  free  will  on  the
screen.  Because  exactly this is the advantage of DER_PROZESS_2.0, to build
flow-sheets on the screen almost without any "nonsense" limits.

But also don't forget to build your flow-sheet in a manner that makes  clear
what you wan with it. It is than more easy for the programme to "understand"
your flow-sheet.

Maybe you ask yourself what is the advantage to make a  flow-sheet  easy  to
understand for the programme ?

Well, it is the factor time. The more clear the funktion of your  flow-sheet
and  the  shorter the length of pipe, the faster the programme will work for
you. And, the way of calculations is easier to do, the  programme  will  not
ask for values which make a calculation possibly but you don't know.

Think about the number of possible calculations for the  massflow  depending
of  the  flow-sheet. Although there is a heatexchanger inside your pipe, you
want to know the massflow calculated through the pressure drop. How  do  the
programme know that ?

If the programme founds while calculating the massflow a  heatexchanger,  it
is then normaly to ask things like thermal power and heat capacities.

So, don't give up when there is a misunderstanding between you and the
programme.

Anyway, it is not a failure of system, when there is a value  the  programme
doesn't  calculate.  It  is  also not the incapability of the programme when
there are things which the programme doesn't understand. And it is also  not
your  ignorance  in  engineering when you will be confronted with unexpected
situations.
Rather you have to see in the work with the programme a simple  dialogue.  A
dialogue between the programme and you when there appears some questions.

In most cases the simple change of a certain value or a tiny change in  your
flow-sheet will enable the obstinacy calculation.

@endnode

@node "Document_23" " An example  "

 An example

There is no profit of the best manual without examples.  This  examples  are
the way to explain things avoiding the theoretically method.
It is not only necessary to show all the pretty functions of this programme,
it  is  also important that the manual of these programme shows the best and
easiest way how to use this programme.

In this example we will see the behaviour of a  heatexchanger  under  normal
conditions  (we  will  heat cold water with thermal oil), but before we will
let calculate some values.


Start   You start in the build mode working with normal units.
        It is the situation after start the programm.

Build   Pressing the help button will show us the report:

        "You are in the build mode.
        Feel free to build up your flow-sheet.
        If you want to see if it is OK, simply press test."

        that we really are in the build mode.
        Now please load without data the flow-sheet

        Beispiel.FLOW

        Besides, it's for the programme the same if you build or you load
        a flow-sheet. In both cases you must test it before use, exept you
        have loaded it with data.

Test    When you are ready with building or with loading, then please test
        your flow-sheet (i.e. press the test button).

Error   And of course, Beispiel.FLOW comes on with an error.
        The report

        "I miss an outlet in this line"

        and a red frame should appear on the screen.
        If you havn't found the error before, you can see now where it is.
        To correct this error move the mouse pointer over the outlet arrow
        button, click one time, move the mouse pointer over the arrow which
        indicates to the top side and click once more again. Now place
        this arrow on the uppermost part (the inlet arrow) of the pipe in
        which you can find the red farme.

Test    Now you can test your flow-sheet again and you will see, your
        flow-sheet is now error free ! The report

        "OK, if you want press 'data'"

        will confirm this.

Data    Now by pressing the data button you can change into the data mode.
        Press the help button and the report

        "You are in the 'data' mode.
        Insert all data you know and which you think necessary for the
        calculations. for each data you want to know input a "?" "

        will confirm it. You can now start with all the data input.
        But it seems necessary at first to know what we want.

        We want

        1.) To calculate the diameter of the water pipe (the pipe in
            which the pump is installed)
        2.) Enter a smaller diameter in the water pipe to calculate then
            the necessary pressure of the pump.
        3.) To observe the thermometer of the water while regulating the
            control valve to vary the flow rate of the thermal oil.
            The flow rate and the outlet temperature of the thermal oil
            and the flow rate of the water we can supervise by observeing
            the corresponding instruments.
        4.) To switch the water pump. Although it is nothing impressive
            to switch this pump, we will do it.

        We have

        1.) All data of thermal oil. In this example we will enter all the
            specific data of the thermal oil, we do not use the thermal oil
            of the substance menu.
        2.) Flowrate (vol) of the pump 20 m3/h
        3.) Water outlet pressure 1.5 bar ü
        4.) Speed of water in the tube, 2 m/s
        5.) Water temperature and thermal oil temperature at the inlet:
            12 und 285 C
        6.) Heat tranfer area and heat transfer coef. of the heatexchanger
            (DER_PROZESS_2.0 is still unable to vary the heat transfer coef.
            in accordance with the flow rate)
        7.) Inlet and outlet pressure of the thermal oil.
        8.) Data of the pipe for thermal oil:
            DN 50; Length 18 m; Roughness 0,08 mm

        At first to commence with the data input of the values we will let
        calculate (diameter of the water pipe). For this we must click a
        part of the water pipe itself (i.e. neither an inlet or outlet nor
        the pump but a part of the pipe) to obtain the data field for this
        pipe. If there is nothing wrong in your work, your lower screen
        part must look like this:

        Pipe ................. Nr >        Flowrate (mass) .... kg/h
        Substance ...............          Speed ............... m/s
        Diametre ............. mm          Length of pipe ........ m
        Temperature ........... C          Zeta-value ............ -
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Roughness ............ mm

        And in your flow-sheet there must be visible a red frame marking
        the corresponding part of the pipe.
        As a real Jeremiah, maybe there isn't any data field on your
        screen. OK, in that case please press help to see in what mode
        you are working. If there is not the data mode indicated, then
        press the data button to change to the data mode.

        For the detailed data input now we can move the ">" with the cursor
        keys up and down (and left and right) or by clicking with the
        mouse pointer on the desired place.

        We want to let calculate by the programme the diametre of the water
        pipe. So, to input a "?" at the diametre place we press on the
        keyboard on the "n" key. And what do we know at this part of the
        flow-sheet ? Only that there flows water with a speed of 2 m/s.
        To enter the "water" we select without moving the ">" the menu point
        substances/liquids/water, immediately in the data field there
        appears

        "water"

        and for the speed we move the ">" to the speed and enter "2".
        Now the data field must look as follows:

        Pipe ................. Nr          Flowrate (mass) .... kg/h
        Substance ...............  water   Speed ............... m/s   2
        Diametre ............. mm   ?      Length of pipe ........ m >
        Temperature ........... C          Zeta-value ............ -
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Roughness ............ mm
                                                                      
        If there is anybody who wants to write a Pipe Nr he can do it.
        We leave the data field by clicking another part of the flow-sheet
        or by clicking the "empty room" inbetween the flow-sheet.
        If you want to control your inputs in the data field, click once
        again on the same part of the flow-sheet. We will notice the
        additionally ".00" on some data.

        Furthermore we want to enter the volumetric flow rate of the water
        pump. That means mouse pointer on the pump and click to obtain the
        necessary data field. I doesn't matter if there is another data
        field open (maybe the one of the water pipe) or not.
        After having entered the flow rate (vol) of the water pump
        the data field should look like this:

        Displ. Pump .......... Nr
        Substance ...............
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h   20
        Pressure ......... bar ue >

        And after the "control click" on the pump, the present data field
        should look like this:

        Displ. Pump .......... Nr >
        Substance ...............
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h   20.00
        Pressure ......... bar ue

        On the water side there is still be missing the inlet temperature.
        After having entered this temperature, the "water inlet data field"
        should look like this:

        Inlet ................ Nr          Flowrate ........... kg/h
        Substance ...............          Density ........... kg/m3
        Pressure ......... bar ue          kinem.Viscos ...... mm2/s
        Temperature ........... C   12     dynam.Viscos ....... mPas
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h >        Spec.heat-cap ... kJ/kg/K

        ...and last but not least on the water side, after having entered
        the outlet pressure, the "water outlet data field" should look like
        this:

        Outlet ............... Nr          Flowrate ........... kg/h
        Substance ...............          Density ........... kg/m3
        Pressure ......... bar ue   1.5    kinem.Viscos ...... mm2/s
        Temperature ........... C >        dynam.Viscos ....... mPas
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Spec.heat-cap ... kJ/kg/K

        And after having entered all the wellknown data of the thermal oil,
        the "thermal oil inlet data field" should look like this

        Inlet ................ Nr          Flowrate ........... kg/h
        Substance ...............          Density ........... kg/m3   830
        Pressure ......... bar ue   6      kinem.Viscos ...... mm2/s
        Temperature ........... C   285    dynam.Viscos ....... mPas   26
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Spec.heat-cap ... kJ/kg/K >
                                                                         
        ...and the "thermal oil outlet data field" :

        Outlet ............... Nr          Flowrate ........... kg/h
        Substance ...............          Density ........... kg/m3
        Pressure ......... bar ue    2.6   kinem.Viscos ...... mm2/s
        Temperature ........... C          dynam.Viscos ....... mPas
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h >        Spec.heat-cap ... kJ/kg/K
                                                                         
        The data field of the thermal oil pipe, i.e. for example the part
        between the inlet and the valve, should look like this:

        Pipe ................. Nr          Flowrate (mass) .... kg/h
        Substance ...............          Speed ............... m/s
        Diametre ............. mm    50    Length of pipe ........ m   18
        Temperature ........... C          Zeta-value ............ - >
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Roughness ............ mm   .08
                                                                             
        And at last we should not forget the heatexchanger. After having
        entered all the correspondig data should look this data field as
        follows:

        Heatexchanger ........ Nr
        Heat-trans-area ...... m2  10
        Heat-trans-coef ..kW/m2/K   .9
        Thermal power ........ kW >

        And that's it !
        If you wonder where there are all the specific values for the
        water, don't forget the "select" of the water by the substances
        menu. With this "select" and with the enter of the water
        temperature (do you remember, 12 C ?) the programme is immediately
        informed internal about all this specific water data.
        Thats the substances menu !

Calc    Finaly we can let the programme calculate.
        So, by pressing the calc button we demand the programme to do for
        what it is developed, to calculate for us !
        After pressing the calc button an the

        ".. mh.."

        of the programme, it will appear the first really comment:

        "...let me see !"

        and a few seconds later there will appear the first result:

        Pipe ................. Nr          Flowrate (mass) .... kg/h
        Substances ..............  water   Speed ............... m/s   2.00
        Diametre ............. mm  59.47   Length of pipe ........ m
        Temperature ........... C          Zeta-value ............ -
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Roughness ............ mm                                                                             

        According to order the diametre has been calculated (= 59.47 mm)
        by the programme. Where this diametre is shows the red frame.

        And now ? If we want to aprise the programme to follow with the
        calculations, we onla need to click one time on the left mouse
        button.

        As there are some instruments to observe later in the action mode,
        the programme follows with the preparation for the simulation,
        because there is nothing more annoying than a missing temperature
        or a missing pressure during a running simulation.

        So, after the click ther will appear the comment:

        "...I'm still on working.."

        And already there is the first question:

        For the calculation of the flowrate (mass) the data of
        cv-value ............ m3/h  _
        would be helpfull

        Also understandable.
        Because the programme is just calculating the flowrate (mass) of
        the thermal oil, the cv-value for the installed valve is needed.
        We enter:

        "12"

        The report

        "...I'm still on working.."

        shows that the programme really is still on working.
        Then the comment

        "...just a moment.."

        appears, and the next question follows:

        For the calculation of the temperature the data of the
        Spec. Heat-cap ... kJ/kg/K  _
        would be helpfull.

        Of course also missing. Because the programme is trying to
        calculate the temperature for the thermometer, and for that the
        spec. heat capacity is needed. We enter:

        "2.2"

        The report

        "...I'm still on working.."

        appears, and after some seconds we can read the final report:

        "I'm ready for action !"

Action  Now, the only thing to do for starting the simulation is to press
        the action button. And after pressing this button, the simulation
        starts and the comment

        "  ...here we go !

        appears.
        Short time later the following list that informs us about the
        units of the values on the instruments will be showed:

        Pressure ..........in bar ue
        Temperature .......in C
        Flowrate (vol) ....in m3/h
        Flowrate (mass) ...in kg/h
        cv-value ..........in m3/h

        And step by step in the display of all the installed instruments
        we can see the present values of temperatures and flowrates.

        Normaly the values of the instruments must be:

        Water temperature            :  12 C und 78 C
        Water flowrate (vol)         :  21 m3/h
        Thermal oil temperature      : 151 C
        Thermal oil flowrate (vol)   :  23 m3/h

        please check them.

        Before adjusting the valve, we will calculate the pump pressure
        that will be necessary after having reduced the diameter.

Data    And that means back to the data mode again by pressing the data
        button. Possibly you must hold down the left mouse button a while
        waiting for the reaction of the data button.
        Once in the data mode, please click the corresponding part in the
        flow-sheet (the part of the water pipe in which there are already
        some data).
        And then, after having entered the new diameter (43 mm) the data
        field must look like:

        Pipe ................. Nr          Flowrate (mass) .... kg/h
        Substances ..............  water   Speed ............... m/s
        Diametre ............. mm   43     Length of pipe ........ m
        Temperature ........... C >        Zeta-value ............ -
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h          Roughness ............ mm
                                                                            
        And after having entered a "?" for the pump pressure to tell the
        programme to calculate the necessary pump pressure, the data field
        of the pump looks like:

        Displ. Pump .......... Nr
        Substances ..............
        Flowrate (vol) ..... m3/h   20.00
        Pressure ......... bar ue    ?

Calc    Now we must press again on the calc button to let the programm
        calculate. Again we recognize it by the comments:

        "..hm.."

        and

        "...let me see !"

        After some time there will appear the question:

        For the calculation of the pressure the data of
        Length of pipe ..... m  _
        will be helpfull

        Of course. The programme needs for the calculation of the pump
        pressure the length of the pipe. We enter

        "22"

        The comment

        "...I'm still on working.."

        shows again the programme is working. And a few seconds later this
        question appears:

        For the calculation of the pressure the data of
        Roughness ... mm  _
        would be helpfull.

        We enter:

        ".15"

        Now after some boring reports at last there appears the result:

        Displ. Pupm .......... Nr
        Substances ..............
        Flowrate (vol)...... m3/h   20.00
        Pressure ......... bar ue    2.55

        And when pressing once more the left mouse button the programme
        continues his work, i.e. with the preparations for the simulation.
        Visible on the reports

        "...I'm still on working.."

        "...just a moment.."

        "I'm ready for action !"

Action  Now we can press again on the action button. After some seconds,
        when all instruments are displaying values, we can start with the
        adjustment of the valve. For this we move the mouse pointer over
        the valve, press and hold down the left mouse button and wait until
        the cv-value on the valve appears. Then, when the cv-value is
        visible, we move slowly the mouse up and down (holding down the
        left mouse button) while observing the increasing and decreasing
        of the cv-value. But, until the left mouse button ist down, all
        calculations are stopped. So, if you will continue the calculations
        you must release the mouse button.
        Now we adjust the new cv-value to

        "15"

        and let the programm to continue with the calculations.
        Step by step there must appear in the instruments the values:

        Water temperatures           :  12 C und 81 C
        Water flowrate (vol)         :  21 m3/h
        Thermal oil temperature      :  168 C
        Thermal oil flowrate (vol)   :  27 m3/h

        Remember to point 4.), we wanted to switch the pump "on" and "off".
        And that means mouse pointer over the pump, than press left mouse
        button till the

        "on"

        display switches into

        "off"

        and the pump is off. Easy, isn't it ?
        The instruments in the running flow-sheet must notice this and
        shows the following:

        Water temperatures           :  12 C und 81 C
        Water flowrate (vol)         :  0 m3/h
        Thermal oil temperature      :  285 C
        Thermal oil flowrate (vol)   :  27 m3/h                    

        In the same way you can switch the pump "on" again.

        At last we will show the power of the unit menu.
        For example we want to show our running plant to an American
        person. The only thing to do is to select from the menu the point
        Units/All Units/US. It doesn't matter in which calculations the
        programme is working.
        The lower unit list must then change into:

        Pressure ..........in psig
        Temperature .......in F
        Flowrate (vol) ....in US.gal/min
        Flowrate (mass) ...in US.gal/min
        cv-value ..........in US.gal/min

        And on the displays of the instruments we must see the following
        values:

        Water temperatures           :   54 F and 178 F
        Water flowrate (vol)         :   91 US.gal/min
        Thermal oil temperature      :  334 C
        Thermal oil flowrate (vol)   :  119 US.gal/min

        And now, feel free to adjust and switch as you like on
        your "running plant".
        This is the purpose of the programme !

There is no more essential to say for the example.

@endnode

@node "Document_24" " What DER_PROZESS_2.0 is unable to"

 What DER_PROZESS_2.0 is unable to 

To know your thought ! You can't imagine how much you suppose  in  that  one
who works for you.

To know your mistakes ! If the data you have entered for a  calculation  are
in any form contradictory and the programme can therefore not calculate, you
will be informed about that disaster.

If you have entered an abundance  of  data  and  there  are  more  than  one
practicable  way  of calculation, the programme will choose the easiest way,
without comparing and checking the other values if they are OK.  Possible  a
reason why you can get confused, because you have expect a totally different
result of the calculations.

If you have builded a totally branched pipe net filled  with  pumps,  valves
etc.  then maybe the programme calculates the requested flowrate through the
pressure drop in a certain piece of pipe instead of finding out the flowrate
making the summary of the flowrate of the other branches.

The air of the substances menu is 100% dry, there is  no  water  inside  and
therefore no dewpoint.

All the gases and the air of the substances menu can't  condense.  They  are
always  gases,  no matter how cold they are and no matter what pressure they
have to suffer. Similar but vice versa the water  of  the  medium  menu.  It
never  evaporates. And the steam of the medium menu is always 100% saturated
steam.

If you send steam through two heatexchangers connected in series,  then  the
steam  condenses  in  each  heatexchanger.  The programme calculates in each
heatexchanger with the hole heat of evaporation.

The programme isn't able to heat up or fill up slowly a tank.  Values  which
increases  or  decreases slowly will not be calculated. All the calculations
are for a "just now" situation.

If there flows a gas (gas or air from the substances menu) through a  valve,
the  pressure drop will be considered or calculated (and with this of course
also the density-drop), but  the  corresponding  temperature  drop  will  be
ignored unless you have entered this value.

The heat tranfer coef. of a heatexchanger will  not  be  influenced  by  the
flowrate through the heatexchanger.

@endnode

@node "Document_25" " The precision of DER_PROZESS_2.0 "

 The precision of DER_PROZESS_2.0


Some words about the precision of the programme. Don't  irritate  about  the
".00"  in  all  the  values  showed  in  the data fields. In most cases this
precision will be reached, because the internal  calculation  will  be  done
with  enough  digits.  But  there  are  values  which  the  programme cannot
calculate with simple  mathematical  formulas.  This  are  for  example  the
flowrates  when  calculated  by  a pressure drop in pipe. The programme must
then try to "find out" a value, that means the programme  "approaches"  step
by  step to a value. And of course this cannot be done wih digits and digits
of precision.

Sometimes also it is possible by the calculations with heatexchangers,  when
there  are  extreme  differences in the flowrates and the temperatures, that
the precision will not be arrived.

But in most  cases  of  practice,  the  precision  of  the  calculations  of
DER_PROZESS_2.0 will be enough.

Also the precision of the values of the substances menu is sometimes not  of
that you maybe expect.

There are a lot of specific data  of  this  substances  which  are  internal
calculated.  Although  this  are  gases,  they  remain "real" gases, so this
specific data may vary from reality.

In clear numbers, the comparison of real and menu data looks like:


                                   Substances menu         Real values

Steam       Pressure (entered)        10.00 bar abs       10.00 bar abs
            Temperature              179.87 C            179.88 C
            Density                    5.14 kg/m3         5.147 kg/m3
            kin.Viscos.                0.01 mPas          0.014 mPas
            dyn.Viscos.                2.89 mm2/s          2.90 mm2/s


                                   Substances menu         Real values

Luft        Pressure    (entered)      5.00 bar abs        5.00 bar abs
            Temperature (entered)    227.00 C            227.00 C
            Density                    3.48 kg/m3         3.472 kg/m3
            kin.Viscos.                0.02 mPas          0.027 mPas
            dyn.Viskos.                7.82 mm2/s         7.776 mm2/s
            spec.heat- cap             1.08 kJ/kg/K       1.032 kJ/kg/K


Know you have your own opinion about the precision of the substances.

@endnode

